            <b>Ethical Implications of Animal Biotechnology:
Considerations for=20
            Animal Welfare Decision Making<br>
            </b>Le Council for Agricultural Science and Technology (CAST)
am=E9ricain=20
            vient de publier un rapport sur les implications =E9thiques des
biotechnologies=20
            appliqu=E9es aux animaux d=92=E9levage. Apres avoir pr=E9cis=E9=
 aussi =AB
scientifiquement=20
            =BB que possible l=92enjeu par rapport aux techniques de
s=E9lection classique,=20
            la nature et les m=E9thodes de ces technologies, le document
aborde=20
            trois grands th=E8mes :<br>
            <br>
            - quelles sont les questions =E9thiques que posent ces
technologies=20
            ?<br>
            - quelles sont leurs cons=E9quences sur les animaux ?<br>
            - quel est l=92impact sur les consommateurs et sur le public en
g=E9n=E9ral=20
            ?<br>
            <br>
            Tenter d=92introduire un peu de rationnel dans ce d=E9bat
largement domin=E9=20
            par toutes sortes de convictions =E9cologiques, religieuses
philosophiques=20
            ou plus simplement financi=E8res ne peut pas faire de mal, m=EA=
me
si ce=20
            document n=92est pas parfait.<br>
            <br>
            Contact : Jean-Paul VIGNAL<br>
            M=E9l : jaypeevee(a)aol.com<br>
            <br>
            See: <a href=3D"http://www.cast-science.org/" target=3D"_blank"
title=3D"Ce lien vers un site externe s'ouvrira dans une nouvelle fen=EAtre=
 ">http://www.cast-science.org/</a><br>
            <br>
            &gt;&gt;&gt; Animal Rights and Wrongs. A New CAST Paper<br>
            <br>
            Although both the Food and Drug Administration and the
European Food=20
            Safety Authority have concluded that meat and milk from
cloned animals=20
            are safe, public perceptions about animal biotechnology
continue to=20
            have an impact on current and potential applications of
existing and=20
            future technologies. To address these and other pressing
issues regarding=20
            the purpose and methods of animal biotechnology, CAST is
releasing=20
            a new paper, <a
href=3D"http://www.cast-science.org/displayProductDetails.asp?idProduct=3D1=
69"
target=3D"_blank"
title=3D"Ce lien vers un site externe s'ouvrira dans une nouvelle fen=EAtre=
 ">Ethical=20
            Implications of Animal Biotechnology: Considerations for
Animal Welfare=20
            Decision Making</a>. This is the final part--Part 9--of the
CAST series=20
            Animal Agriculture's Future through Biotechnology. (June
2010)<br>
            <br>
            &gt;&gt;&gt; Animal Rights and Wrongs: New CAST Paper
Considers Ethics=20
            of Animal Biotechnology<br>
            <br>
            June 7, 2010. Ames, Iowa. Animal biotechnology=97which includes
both=20
            genetic engineering and mammalian cloning=97has expanded
rapidly in=20
            recent decades. These technologies already have been applied
in biomedical=20
            research and now are nearing application within the food
system. Public=20
            opinion studies regarding animal biotechnology reveal that
people=20
            are concerned about the purpose of the applications, the
methods of=20
            research, and the objects of manipulation.<br>
            <br>
            To address these concerns, CAST is releasing a new Issue
Paper, <i>Ethical=20
            Implications of Animal Biotechnology: Considerations for
Animal Welfare=20
            Decision Making. </i>This is the final part=97Part 9=97of the
CAST series=20
            <i>Animal Agriculture=92s Future through Biotechnology. </i>The
authors=20
            discuss three broad categories of ethical issues associated
with animal=20
            biotechnology, including the impact on the animals
themselves, the=20
            institutions and procedures that govern the research and
applications=20
            within the agrifood system, and the relationships between
humans and=20
            other animals. Topics examined in the paper include<br>
            <br>
            - General overview of animal biotechnology science<br>
            - Genetics in conventional animal breeding programs<br>
            - Ethical issues overview<br>
            - Religious views on animal biotechnology<br>
            - Public perceptions of animal biotechnology<br>
            - Regulation of animal biotechnology<br>
            <br>
            =93Decisions about the future development and use of animal
biotechnology=20
            may be more effective and widely accepted if parties from
various=20
            disciplines increase their commitment to frequent and
sustained cooperative=20
            efforts,=94 according to Task Force Chair Paul B. Thompson and
his coauthors=20
            of the new CAST Issue Paper.<br>
            <br>
            =93Many people do not have an accurate understanding of the
methods=20
            and purposes of animal biotechnology,=94 says CAST Executive
Vice President=20
            John Bonner. =93CAST is pleased to offer scientific information
in this=20
            new paper that will help people consider the ethical
questions associated=20
            with agricultural animal biotechnology.=94<br>
            <br>
            Thompson=97Department of Philosophy and Department of
Community, Agriculture,=20
            Recreation, and Resource Studies, Michigan State University,
East=20
            Lansing=97will join Bonner at the National Coalition for Food
and Agricultural=20
            Research =93Lunch-n-Learn Seminar=94 in Washington, D.C. on
Monday, June=20
            7, to present the paper. Thompson is also scheduled to be a
speaker=20
            at the CAST food-animal agriculture symposium,<br>
            <i>Sustaining Animal Agriculture: Balancing Bioethical,
Economic,=20
            &amp; Social Issues</i>, on June 9.<br>
            <br>
            <i>Ethical Implications of Animal Biotechnology:
Considerations for=20
            Animal Welfare Decision Making</i>; <i>Animal Agriculture=92s
Future=20
            through Biotechnology, Part 9</i> (IP46, 16 pp.) is available
at the=20
            CAST website (<a href=3D"http://www.cast-science.org/../../"
target=3D"_blank"
title=3D"Ce lien vers un site externe s'ouvrira dans une nouvelle fen=EAtre=
 ">www.cast-science.org</a>)=20
            for free download, in addition to the other 8 parts in this
series.=20
            All Issue Papers also are available in hard copy from the
CAST office=20
            (515-292-2125); a shipping/handling fee applies. CAST is an
international=20
            consortium of scientific and professional societies. It
assembles,=20
            interprets, and communicates credible science-based
information regionally,=20
            nationally, and internationally to legislators, regulators,
policymakers,=20
            the media, the private sector, and the public.<br>
            See: <a
href=3D"http://www.cast-science.org/displayProductDetails.asp?idProduct=3D1=
69"
target=3D"_blank"
title=3D"Ce lien vers un site externe s'ouvrira dans une nouvelle fen=EAtre=
 ">http://www.cast-science.org/displayProductDetails.asp?idProduct=3D169</a=
